2 Staff Handbook
2.1 Introduction
This handbook is a synopsis of policies governing staff of QMSrs and is not intended to represent
contractual terms of employment. The policies outlined in this document may change after the
publication date. QMSrs reserves the right to change, or discontinue without notice, any plan,
program, benefit, term or condition set forth within this handbook.
More detailed interpretation and administration of these policies are made by the Department of
Human Resources (HR).
Changes will be posted on (www.qmsrs.org).
2.2 Who is QMSrs?
QMSrs system is developed by a team of leading authorities with well over 25 years of
industrial experience in introducing and maintaining quality management systems at
global giants, covering Governments and Commercial Giants.
Each industry has its own unique requirements and quality criteria. QMSrs solutions are
designed to deliver best practices for each of our specialised industries. Our specialists in
these industries have built solid expertise and relationships with leading edge partners
within these industries. You can harness these experts and relationships through the
implementation of these best practices. Some of the industries we have presence in are
listed below:
IT
Construction
Pharmaceutical
Medical Devices
Government
Oil & Gas
Manufacturing
Automotive
Food & Beverage
We specialise in Quality Management Systems only and therefore focussed on providing
a specialist service in this sector of the industry
Our solutions are suitable for any size organisation from small to multi-site global
organisation

2.6 Environmental Safety and Health
QMSrs is committed to ensuring a safe work environment for employees by strictly adhering to
legal requirements governing environmental health and safety in the workplace. This includes:
Provide health and safety workplace; provide healthy equipments in working environment to
insure staff and visitors safety.
2.7 Smoking
Our policy of no smoking on the premises must be observed at all times.
2.8 Workplace Violence
QMSrs is committed to maintain a work environment that is as free as possible from acts or
threats of violence or intimidation. The safety and security of staff and visitors are of vital
importance. Violent or threatening behavior will not be tolerated. This policy applies to any acts
of violence or threats made on QMSrs property, at QMSrs events, or under other circumstances
that may negatively affect QMSrs ability to conduct business

2.9 Job Specifications and Descriptions
Job Specifications were developed and generally describe the primary duties and responsibilities
of the work to be performed, the minimum qualifications necessary to perform the job, and
educational requirements. These specifications are used system-wide and cannot be changed,
deleted, or amended without the approval of the top management.
Job descriptions are created by the HR and Quality managers.
2.10 Job Evaluation/Position Allocation
Our policy is to monitor your work performance on a continuous basis so that we can maximize
your strengths, and help you overcome any possible weaknesses.
Each position in the state personnel system is assigned to a specific class. If the permanent duties
of your job change significantly, your position may be evaluated to determine the correct class
based on an official job description.
Department HR offices usually process evaluations of positions in their organizations. As a result
of an evaluation, your position can move to a higher or lower class or can remain in its current
class.
If your position is allocated to a higher class, you may compete for the position. If you do
not meet the minimum qualifications for the new class, you will begin the layoff process.
If your position is allocated to a lower level and you are certified, you may choose to
demote in your position, have your name placed on a reemployment list for your former
class, and your base pay will remain the same, including saved pay. If you do not choose
the demotion option, layoff provisions apply. If you are a probationary employee, you
may demote to the position in lieu of layoff if you qualify for the new class.
2.11 Work Schedules
Employees work a standard workweek of (10) hours per day, 40 hours per week and (2) hours for
launch break and two days holiday/ week. Employees may be required to different work
schedules as necessary to meet work needs.
2.12 Overtime
We pay overtime for hours exceed 40 hours per week for 125% of employee salary for each extra
hour.
If the employee worked in week end or in formal holiday, we will pay 150% of his salary for each
extra day.
2.13 Employee Training
At the beginning of new employment, the employee will receive training for his/ her specific job,
and as his/ her employment progresses his/ her skills may be extended to encompass new job
activities within QMSrs.

2.14 Job Flexibility
It is an express condition of employment that you are prepared, whenever necessary, to transfer to
alternative departments or duties within QMSrs. During holiday periods, etc. it may be necessary
for you to take over some duties normally performed by colleagues. This flexibility is essential as
the type and volume of work is always subject to change, and it allows us to operate efficiently
and gain maximum potential.
2.15 Salary
The salary ranges depend on job classes. The salary may only be changed with the review and
approval of top management upon the recommendation of direct manager.
2.16 Probation
Probation is a trial period in which employees demonstrate their ability to perform the duties and
responsibilities of the position.
Newly hired employees serve a three-month original, probationary period, upon the successful
completion of probation.
2.17 Performance Evaluation
Effective performance evaluation involves communication between the employee and the
supervisor of expectations, goals, and the standards for measuring performance.
2.18 Conduct and Discipline
Employees are expected to perform their work efficiently and effectively and to be mindful of the
expectations of QMSrs and its employees. As such, employees are expected to act effectively and
integrity at all times. Managers are expected to provide leadership for the group they manage, to
respect the dignity and rights of employees as individuals, and to set an example by their own
conduct, attitude, and work habits.
Appropriate disciplinary measures should be applied firmly, consistently, impartially, and where
required, appropriate disciplinary action will be administered to ensure continued effective and
efficient operation of QMSrs.
2.19 Confidentiality and Conflict of Commitment
Employees are expected to adhere to rules prohibiting dissemination of private and/or
confidential information related to employee personal data and work information. Depending
upon the type of work involved, a campus department may have confidentiality agreements in
force.
By accepting appointment at QMSrs, each employee is expected to perform assigned duties and
responsibilities. Any outside/external commitments shall not interfere with the execution of
assigned duties and responsibilities nor compromise existing work and research being conducted
at QMSrs.
2.20 Sick Leave
Regular employees earn 14 days of sick leave per year. There is no compensation for
unused sick leave at termination of employment.
